Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Sheep affected with salmonella often have a death rate of approximately 1-2 percent but that can reach up to 5 percent. Apart from the deaths, salmonellosis can play havoc with normal management, especially close to mating time.

Affected sheep become very depressed, develop severe diarrheoa, and usually die within a few days.

Diagnosis is based on clinical signs and history and is confirmed by autopsy and culture of intestinal contents.

Outbreaks can be dramatic with a high death rate in a short time. But many outbreaks tend to be innocuous with "the odd ewe dying" until numbers get large enough for the farmer to become concerned.

Prevention is best achieved by vaccination. Vaccination in the face of the outbreak will most likely reduce losses, whether the ewes have been sensitized or not. It is very easy to put vaccinating off because of the cost and the need for gathering the animals, which poses a risk of spreading the disease. Cost is around NZD 80-100 [USD 65-81] per ewe. If ewes are worth NZD 150 each [USD 121], vaccination needs to save 2 percent of the ewes.

Portions of this comment have been extracted from: http://www.vetent.co.nz/sheep-beef-deer-disease-management/salmonella.html.

Southland, New Zealand may be found on the interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at: http://healthmap.org/r/6XxC. - Mod.TG]
